release.name: QZ nightly build 20250817
release.body:
This is a nightly build of QZ.

You can use this if you want to try new features without waiting for releases.
From time to time, in development builds, old difficult-to-reproduce bugs are
fixed, but it is also true that in the development process with the introduction
of new complex code, the stability of the program may suffer compared to
official releases, so **use it with caution**!

## Windows Builds:
- **windows-msvc2019**: Recommended for Windows 10
- **windows-msvc2022**: Recommended for Windows 11 (experimental, QT6)
- **windows**: MinGW build (alternative version)

## Other Platforms:
- **fdroid-android-trial**: Android build
- **nordictrack-android-trial**: Nordictrack build for iFIT2 Tablets
- **raspberry-pi-binary**: Raspberry Pi build

__Please help us improve QZ by reporting any issues you encounter!__ :wink:

pull_request.title: Feat/support
pull_request.body:
# Pull Request

## Description  
This PR enhances the Help ‚Üí FAQ page UI/UX and updates i18n resources for both English (en) and Korean (ko).

### What‚Äôs changed
 - Accordion UX polish
  - Fully hides collapsed content (no peek-through): conditional py-0, opacity-0, pointer-events-none, aria-hidden
  - Smooth transition of max-height, padding, and opacity
  - Accessible toggles via aria-expanded/aria-controls
- Category tabs + Search workflow
  - Tabs: booking, payment, account, policy, technical
  - Stabilized search: split input into input (typing state) and searchTerm (confirmed via Enter or Search button) to avoid list ‚Äújumping‚Äù
  - Cross-category search when a query is confirmed: matches question/answer text and category title (e.g., searching ‚Äúrefund‚Äù surfaces items in the Payment group even if Booking tab is selected)
  - Clear button resets search and re-enables tabs
  - Results show grouped by category in search mode; in non-search mode, only active tab items are shown
  - Result count indicator
- CTA & contact link
  - ‚ÄúStill need help?‚Äù section with button linking to /${locale}/help/contact
- Accessibility
  - Labels for inputs, aria-disabled for tabs during search, keyboard handling (Enter to search)
- i18n updates (en/ko)
  - Added common keys: common.search, common.clear
  - Added helper strings: faq.searchingAll, improved faq.resultsCount, faq.empty, faq.subtitle, faq.cta.*, faq.feedback.*
  - Ensured FAQ data loaded via returnObjects: true is handled safely
- Locale-aware routing
  - Link to contact page uses /${locale}/help/contact to avoid duplicate prefixes or missing locale
- Refactor / safety
  - Guarded i18n array access with getQnaArray
  - useMemo used for derived lists to avoid unnecessary recalculations
- (SEO optional)
  - Removed dynamic JSON-LD that changed on each keystroke; can re-introduce a stable, limited FAQPage schema in a follow-up if desired

## Why  
- Prevents the content area from ‚Äúpeeking‚Äù when collapsed
- Avoids motion sickness from list re-rendering on every keystroke
- Lets users find items via category keywords (e.g., ‚ÄúÌôòÎ∂à / refund‚Äù) even if they‚Äôre on a different tab
- Improves accessibility and clarity
- Keeps translations consistent and ready for future growth of FAQ content

## Testing  
Local steps
1. Navigate to /{locale}/help (e.g., /ko/help, /en/help).
2. Accordion
  - Click a question ‚Üí content expands smoothly.
  - Click again ‚Üí content fully hides (no residual spacing or opacity).
3. Tabs
  - Click different category tabs and confirm only that category‚Äôs items render.
4. Search (confirmed mode)
  - Type a keyword (e.g., ‚Äúrefund‚Äù / ‚ÄúÌôòÎ∂à‚Äù) but do not press Enter ‚Üí list should not change.
  - Press Enter or click Search ‚Üí search mode activates; results grouped by category appear; tabs dim/disable.
  - Click Clear ‚Üí search mode ends; tabs reactive; original tab list returns.
5. Category keyword search
  - From any tab, search a category term (e.g., typing ‚Äúpayment‚Äù or ‚ÄúÍ≤∞Ï†ú‚Äù) and confirm results from that category appear.
6. Contact link
  - Click ‚ÄúContact Support‚Äù ‚Üí navigates to /${locale}/help/contact.
7. i18n
  - Switch between en and ko locales; verify all labels/buttons/text render correctly.

## Linked Issues  
None

## Checklist  
<!-- 
Mark completed items with an [x]  
-->
- [x] Code builds and runs locally  
- [ ] Component or util func created  
- [ ] Page layout added  
- [x] Tests (if any) pass  
- [ ] I have reviewed my code for clarity and best practices

release.name: Video Transcriber v1.0.0 - First Release
release.body:
## üéâ Video Transcriber v1.0.0

First official release of the Video Transcriber desktop application!

### ‚ú® Features
- üé• Convert MP4, AVI, MKV, MOV videos to text transcripts
- üöÄ GPU acceleration support (10-20x faster with NVIDIA GPUs)
- üì¶ Batch processing with queue management
- üßπ Advanced text processing with filler word removal
- üíæ Custom Whisper model loading support
- ‚è∏Ô∏è Pause/resume functionality
- üìä Real-time progress tracking

### üì• Installation
‚ö†Ô∏è **Note**: Due to GitHub's file size limitations, the executable is not included as a release asset. Please build from source or contact the developer for distribution alternatives.

**To build from source:**
1. Clone this repository
2. Install dependencies: `pip install -r requirements.txt`
3. Run: `python run.py`

### üéØ Whisper Model Setup
The app requires Whisper AI models to function. On first use:
- The app will auto-download models (requires internet)
- OR load pre-downloaded models using "Load Model Folder" button

Model sizes available:
- **tiny** (39MB) - Very fast, basic quality
- **base** (74MB) - Fast, good quality  
- **small** (244MB) - Moderate speed, better quality
- **medium** (769MB) - Slow, very good quality
- **large** (1.5GB) - Very slow, best quality

### üñ•Ô∏è System Requirements
- Windows 10/11
- 8GB RAM minimum (16GB recommended)
- NVIDIA GPU recommended for faster processing
- 4GB free disk space

### üìù Notes
- First run may take time to load models
- GPU acceleration requires NVIDIA CUDA-capable GPU
- Large video files are automatically split for processing

### üêõ Known Issues
- Large executable size (2-3GB) due to bundled ML libraries
- Initial model loading can be slow
- Executable too large for GitHub release assets

### üìö Documentation
See the [README](https://github.com/dusancv22/Video-Transcriber-App) for detailed usage instructions.

---

issue.title: Inconsistent tagging of slicing-related plugins
issue.body:
While searching plugins that implement OctoPrint's slicing functionality, I noticed that they are tagged inconsistently, which makes them harder to find.

Current state:
- [PrePrintService](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/preprintservice/): tags `slic3r`, `slicing`
- [Slic3r](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/slic3r/): tag `slic3r`
- [Full-featured Slicer](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/slicer/): tag `slicer`
- [CuraEngine Legacy](https://plugins.octoprint.org/plugins/curalegacy/): tag `slicer`

It would be useful to unify the tagging of slicing-related plugins (e.g. consistently using either `slicer` or `slicing`, what you prefer) in order to improve discoverability.

In addition, I noticed that a new plugin called InternalSlicer was recently created. In [this forum discussion](https://community.octoprint.org/t/plugin-octoprint-internal-slicer/57514), I invited the maintainer to add it to this repository as well.

performed_via_github_app.name: Socket Security
performed_via_github_app.description:
### Socket protects your app from malicious dependencies lurking in your open source supply chain.

Open source code makes up 90% of most codebases. It is critical to manage it effectively to reduce your security risk.

## Detect and block open source supply chain attacks

Security teams depend on Socket to prevent malicious open source dependencies from infiltrating their apps.

Socket dramatically improves your open source security posture by _detecting and blocking the attacks you don't expect_ ‚Äì malware, install scripts, hidden code, typo-squatting, and more ‚Äì which aren't caught by traditional vulnerability scanners.

- **Block malware** ‚Äì Block emerging malware threats

- **Block typo-squatting** ‚Äì Block malicious packages that differ in name by only a few characters, and recommend the correct package

- **Detect hidden code** ‚Äì Detect obfuscated, minified, or hidden code

- **Detect privileged API usage** ‚Äì Report when a dependency update introduces new risky API usage ‚Äì filesystem, network, child_process, eval()

- **Detect suspicious updates** ‚Äì Sudden inclusion of privileged APIs in patch or minor releases

Socket currently [supports 60 detections](https://socket.dev/npm/issue) in 5 categories: supply chain risk, quality, maintenance, known vulnerabilities, and license problems.

## Take charge of your dependency health

Socket improves security outcomes and reduces work for security teams by **surfacing actionable security information directly inline in GitHub** so developers are empowered to make better decisions.

- **Five minute deployment** ‚Äì The easiest security product you'll ever deploy in your organization. Just install a GitHub app and you're done.

- **Provide security feedback directly on PRs** ‚Äì Empower developers to solve security issues before they're deployed into production.

- **Automated security** ‚Äì Spend security team resources auditing the highest-impact dependencies, instead of all or nothing.

## Socket detects what vulnerability scanners can‚Äôt

It's no longer sufficient to scan for known vulnerabilities (CVEs) and stop there. And yet, that's what the leading "supply chain security" products do, leaving you vulnerable.

It can take weeks or months for a CVE to be discovered, reported, and detected by tools. But in today's culture of fast development, a malicious dependency can be updated, merged, and running in production in days or even sometimes hours.

Defenders need a new approach to address emerging threats from malicious dependencies:

- **Maintainer intentionally added malware** ‚Äì Rogue maintainer sabotaged his own open source package with 100M downloads/month, affecting companies such as Amazon AWS

- **Package hijacked and poisoned w/ cryptominers and password-stealing malware** ‚Äì Deliberate malware introduced into multiple packages with 30M downloads/month each

- **Package hijacked to add backdoor targeting a specific organization** ‚Äì Obfuscated malware added to a dependency which targeted a single company, went undetected for over a week, and made it into their production build

- **NPM package manager allowed anyone to publish new versions of any package** ‚Äì Attackers could publish new versions of any NPM package without authorization _for multiple years_

Using third-party dependencies without proper vetting leaves you open to hacking, breaches, and assorted security misfortune.
